<br>
Mage pets start to dual wield at 24.  Necro pets start to dual wield at 29.  I can't comment on other classes of pets.  At these levels, you must give your pet two one handed weapons to force the pet to dual wield.  At higher levels, pets automatically dual wield.  I've recently been leveling a necro and I think for necro pets that level is 39.  I can't remember which set of pets it is for mages, but it is either 34 or 39.  Once again, not sure on other classes of pets.  For charmed pets, I believe you always have to give them weapons to make them dual wield.  Frequently charmed pets won't take two of the same type of weapon (2 walnan blades for example).  When duoing with an enchanter dire charming, I usually give one walnan blade, then one dagger of symbols since I don't have a second type of procy weapon.<br>
<br>
Procy weapons have a pretty high level requirement to allow them to actually proc.  The earliest a necro pet will proc a walnan blade is the level 49 pet spell (and the proc rate is REALLY low.  maybe one per a one and a half minute fight if lucky).  I haven't tested it out on mage pets yet.  Maybe one day.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but pre-50, what would you say the best combo of weapons available through summoning would be?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Any one handed weapon will be as good as another.  All you are doing is forcing the pet to dual wield.  At higher levels, pets ignore the damage rating on the weapon, so a weapon with a higher damage rating means nothing.  Pets haven't cared about the weapon's delay in years, so the delay on a weapon doesn't matter.  Having said that, the level 1 dagger is no worse than the level 39 dagger.<br>
<br>
Sometimes a high level pet will equip the summoned shield in his off hand and sometimes he won't.  I haven't figured out what triggers it to do so one time and not the other.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My casual observation is fluffy hits more times for max dmg with something in hand <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
There have been several long parses by reliable mages regarding this idea.  This idea pops up most by mages who think the rogue pets do more damage with daggers than bare handed or with non piercing weapons.  The parses show there is zero difference in damage output.<br>
<br>
